guous symbol that was masking a real test\n\nGaps and weaknesses:\n\n1. **No positive test for quoted digits in format directives.** The initial 2872.test (commit `6f206454`) tested `commodity \"CTG25\"` with `format 1000.000 \"CTG25\"` as a success case (`test source -> 0`). When the commit `28feca2e` updated the test to exercise the new diagnostic, the success case (quoted commodity with digits) was removed entirely. There is no regression test confirming that `format 1000.000 \"CTG25\"` (quoted, valid) still works. This is a gap — the fix could conceivably break valid quoted-digit format directives without being detected.\n\n2. **No test for trailing whitespace.** The fix uses `if (in >> trailing)` — trailing whitespace is skipped by `>>`. There is no test confirming that `format 1000.000 CTG ` (trailing spaces) does NOT trigger the error.\n\n3. **Error message line number.** The expected error says `line 21`. If the test file layout ever changes, this becomes a maintenance burden. (Minor — this is a known test format convention.)\n\n4. **No test for multiple trailing tokens.** Only one trailing token (`25`) is tested; no test for `CTG25 abc` or similar.\n\n---\n\n### Fix #2008 — strip journal-syntax quotes from commodity names in CSV output\n\n**Source changes:**\n- `src/value.cc`: `to_string()` for COMMODITY type changed from `symbol()` to `base_symbol()`\n\n**Test files:**\n- `/Users/johnw/src/ledger/check-tests/test/regress/2008.test` (new)\n\n**Coverage assessment:**\n\nStrengths:\n- Tests the exact reported bug: commodity `\"l33tc0in\"` (quoted in journal) should appear as `l33tc0in` (unquoted) in CSV output\n- Tests both postings in the transaction (crypto side and counterpart £ side)\n- Verifies complete CSV output row format\n\nGaps and weaknesses:\n\n1. **Only tests via `csv` command.** The `value_t::to_string()` for COMMODITY type is a lower-level function used in several contexts (e.g., string concatenation via `operator+=`). The fix could affect places other than CSV output, but only CSV is tested.\n\n2. **No test for `symbol()` vs `base_symbol()` difference for non-quoted commodities.** For commodities like `$` or `EUR` (no quoting needed), `symbol()` and `base_symbol()` return the same string. The test only covers a commodity that requires quoting. There is no test confirming unquoted commodities are unaffected by this change.\n\n3. **No test for the coverage-wave7-report-opts.test CSV test with AAPL.** The AAPL commodity in that file is unquoted; if it were quoted (e.g., `\"AAPL\"`), this fix would affect it. The 2008.test specifically uses a commodity that requires quoting, which is correct, but there's no broader regression suite for this code path.\n\n4. **The `fn_commodity()` function in report.cc uses `symbol()` directly, not `to_string()`.** When `%(commodity(...))` is called in a format string, it goes through `fn_commodity()` which calls `.commodity().symbol()` — not the fixed `to_string()` path. The 2008 fix only affects the COMMODITY-type branch of `to_string()`, which is hit when a `value_t` of type COMMODITY is converted to string. It is unclear from tests alone whether `%(commodity(scrub(display_amount)))` in the CSV format actually goes through `value_t::to_string()` or through `fn_commodity()`. The 2008.test verifies the behavior is correct but doesn't clarify which code path is exercised.\n\n---\n\n### Fix #1227 — print/xact/dump to respect 'not' in positional queries\n\n**Source changes:**\n- `src/report.cc`: Added `wrap_xact_predicate()` helper; refactored `parse_query_args()` to use AST manipulation rather than string hacking; queries for `print`, `xact`, `dump` commands are now wrapped in `any()` at AST level\n- `src/op.h`: Added `#include`\n\n**Test files:**\n- `/Users/johnw/src/ledger/check-tests/test/regress/1227.test` (new)\n\n**Coverage assessment:**\n\nStrengths:\n- Tests the primary bug: `print not :pension` now excludes the pension transaction entirely (not shows all three)\n- Tests positive filter (`print :pension`) for regression baseline\n- Tests `not payee Pension` variant (payee-based negation)\n- Tests `payee Pension` positive case for completeness\n\nGaps and weaknesses:\n\n1. **`xact` and `dump` commands are not tested.** The fix applies to three commands (`print`, `xact`, `dump`) as shown in `normalize_options()`. Only `print` is tested in 1227.test. The `xact` command as a filter for displaying transactions (not the draft-transaction xact) and `dump` are not tested with `not` queries.\n\n2. **No test for double-negation or complex `not` expressions.** The fix transforms `O_NOT(inner)` to `O_NOT(O_CALL(\"any\", inner))`. There is no test for `not not :pension` or `not (:pension and :foo)` which would exercise different AST shapes.\n\n3. **No test for account regex queries.** The issue mentions `not account =~ /pension/` as a workaround that already worked. No test verifies that `print not account =~ /pension/` (a regex-based not) also works correctly with the new fix.\n\n4. **No test for the `dump` command at all.** While `dump` is referenced in `normalize_options`, it is not dispatched in the command lookup table (`report.cc` switch statement). It may be an alias or unused. It is not tested.\n\n5. **No test with 4+ transactions.** With only 3 transactions, there is some ambiguity about edge cases. A test with more varied data (some matching, some not) would provide stronger coverage.\n\n6. **Refactor correctness.** The refactor from string-manipulation to AST manipulation (`ac2b250d`) is not independently tested — 1227.test was written before the refactor and covers the same cases. The refactor introduced `query.parse_args()` which returns an AST directly; if this API has subtly different semantics than `query.get_query()`, the refactor could introduce a regression that 1227.test would not detect.\n\n---\n\n### Fix #2871 — remove invalid ((@)) virtual price indicator syntax\n\n**Source changes:**\n- `src/annotate.cc`: Removed looka